sec.p:
The numerical model was established using identical geometry and engineering parameters as the physical model, maintaining the same boundary conditions. The screw geometry is the same for each angle of inclination used which means the operated head for the power increases when the angle of inclination increases. From a theoretical view, the highest inclination angle for the screw will generate the maximum power in the experiments. The inclination angle (35




        ∘



) generates power more than the inclination angle (30




        ∘



). This means the losses associated with the screw are not considered when changing the inclination angle to more or less the optimum angle (35




        ∘



). For the angles with a slope lower than the optimum angle, the minor losses in the screw will play the most role cause total losses. However, in angles with a steep optimal slope, the losses due to gaps and overflow will be more significant. When high flow rates occur, there's a high overflow reducing efficiency.
